- Saunders saturation calls
    - format: one entry per chapter when first-pass extraction completes
    - entry shape:
        - what came out of this chapter
        - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - why those did not make it
        - decision: saturated | re-sweep needed

- Chapter 1: Front Matter (copyright, table of contents, epigraph)
    - what came out: nothing
    - what didn't make the gate: not applicable. The chapter is bibliographic metadata (copyright, TOC, an epigraph). It contains no teaching content from which moves could be extracted.
    - why: the chapter is structural front matter, not authorial argument or demonstration.
    - decision: saturated (vacuously, with zero skills)

- Chapter 2: We Begin
    - what came out: the-basic-drill, ask-strategic-not-interpretive, is-it-helping
    - what didn't make the gate:
        - keeping a small set of touchstone stories as a high bar (autobiographical aside, no concrete action)
        - workbook stance, going deeper than a first read allows (folded into the-basic-drill, which is the actual mechanism)
        - reading from the reader's experience as such (parent-context lens already captured in _book.md)
        - iconic space, resistance literature, rhetorical trial balloons (parent-context vocabulary already in _book.md; the only one that yielded an atomic move was the trial-balloon disposition, promoted as is-it-helping)
    - why: the chapter is mostly framing, lens-setting, and vocabulary already absorbed into _book.md as parent context. The three skills that survive each name a concrete reader/writer/teacher action with an observable signal and a recognizable failure mode, distinct from the lens itself. The dropped items are either vague or already covered.
    - decision: saturated

- Chapter 3: A Page at a Time
    - what came out: page-break-diagnostic, hollywood-version, cornfeld-principle, ritual-banality-avoidance, two-version-comparison, increasing-specification, truncation-test
    - what didn't make the gate:
        - bowling pins / juggler metaphor for tracking expectations (folded into page-break-diagnostic, which is the procedural form Saunders gives this idea)
        - structure as call-and-response between questions raised and answers supplied (folded into page-break-diagnostic for the same reason)
        - cross-painting characters with contradictory traits (folded into increasing-specification as one technique within the larger move)
        - variation against stasis when a beat repeats (dropped: action "vary it" too vague, no concrete signal that distinguishes good variation)
        - the motorcycle-and-sidecar metaphor for reader-writer closeness (dropped: evocative model rather than procedure, no concrete action or measurable signal)
        - "ruthless efficiency principle" as standalone (overlaps too tightly with cornfeld-principle, which is the procedural test the REP demands; folded by reference within cornfeld-principle's framing)
        - story-as-system-for-energy-transfer (dropped: a powerful image with no procedural form independent of the moves already promoted, especially ritual-banality-avoidance and truncation-test)
        - "Is it story yet?" as a slogan (folded into truncation-test, which is the actual mechanism for answering it)
    - why: this chapter is unusually rich because Saunders teaches by demonstrating multiple procedural moves in sequence on a single Chekhov story. Many candidates surfaced; the gate forced consolidation. Each promoted skill names a distinct situation and a distinct procedure, with no two doing the same work at different specificity. The dropped items are either evocative metaphors without independent procedural form (motorcycle/sidecar, energy transfer) or restatements of moves already promoted under sharper names (REP under cornfeld-principle, "Is it story yet?" under truncation-test, structure-as-call-and-response under page-break-diagnostic). Seven skills is at the upper end of the chapter's length budget but the chapter genuinely does the work to support each one.
    - decision: saturated
